response:
 This problem is equivalent to finding the number left after you subtract 9 from a number with 51 zeros. We can go from the exponent to the digits by dividing the number by 10 each time until we meet 9. But, we also have to add one to the quotient when the one digit of the number is bigger than 9. \begin{align*}
\dfrac{10^{51} - 9}{10} &= 10^{50} - 0.9 < 90\\
\dfrac{10^{50} - 0.9}{10} &= 10^{49} - 0.09 < 90\\
&~\vdots
\end{align*> The calculated quotient of each division is a number containing digit zeros. When the first time the one digit of our number is bigger than 9, we have to add 1 to the quotient to carry on our operation. The first time this occurs is at the 50th division \begin{align*}
\dfrac{10^{50} - 0.09}{10} &= 10^{49} - 0.009\\
&= \boxed{100 \, 000 \, 000 \, 000 \, 000 \, 000 \, 000}
\end{align*}. Our answer is $\boxed{91}$. <answer> 91 </answer>

